<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="surveys">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Collect quantitative data from N≥100 users via standardized instruments (NPS, SUS, CSAT, SEQ) to validate qualitative findings and measure user attitudes at scale.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>research</tag>
      <tag>surveys</tag>
      <tag>quantitative</tag>
      <tag>user-research</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Surveys and Questionnaires</title>
    <summary>A research method for collecting structured data from large user populations through standardized questions — covering satisfaction (NPS, CSAT, SUS), task ease (SEQ), and feature preference — to quantify user attitudes and validate qualitative findings at scale.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Qualitative research (interviews, diary studies) produces rich insight but cannot generalize across a user base. Surveys close that gap by reaching N≥100 with standardized instruments whose benchmarks are well-established (SUS average=68, NPS range −100 to +100). Without surveys, product teams rely on the loudest voices and cannot segment findings by user type or measure change over time.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quantitative validation of qualitative findings at N≥100.</item>
        <item>Tracking standard UX metrics over time: NPS, SUS, CSAT, SEQ.</item>
        <item>Segmenting users (new vs. power, free vs. paid) to measure satisfaction or feature value.</item>
        <item>Pre/post launch comparison of perceived ease, trust, or feature impact.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>You do not yet know which questions to ask — run interviews first; an ill-formed survey produces noise.</item>
        <item>Sample &lt;30 — descriptive statistics are unreliable; use qualitative methods instead.</item>
        <item>You need behavioral data (clicks, time on task) — analytics or usability tests, not self-report.</item>
        <item>High-stakes decisions where social-desirability bias dominates (e.g., willingness-to-pay overestimated 2-4x by surveys).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Survey Types">
      <list>
        <item>Satisfaction — measures user happiness with a product or experience (CSAT, NPS).</item>
        <item>Task-based — collects post-task feedback on ease and usability (SUS, SEQ).</item>
        <item>Preference — compares options or prioritizes features (A vs B, ranking).</item>
        <item>Exploratory — understands usage patterns and behaviors at scale.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Six-Step Survey Design Process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define a specific, measurable research objective before writing any question; never start with question ideas and work backward to an objective.</statement>
        <rationale>Ill-formed objectives produce questions that collect data no one acts on; a clear objective constrains the question set and prevents survey bloat.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Step 1: Define objective — what specific, measurable thing do you want to know?</item>
        <item>Step 2: Choose question types — multiple choice for fixed options, rating scale for intensity, ranking for prioritization, open-ended only for exploration.</item>
        <item>Step 3: Write questions — one concept per question, neutral wording, complete answer options.</item>
        <item>Step 4: Design flow — introduction + consent → screening → easy questions → core questions → demographics → thank you.</item>
        <item>Step 5: Pilot test with 5-10 people; time the median completion; fix any confusion before launch.</item>
        <item>Step 6: Analyze — calculate response rate, descriptive statistics on quantitative items, theme-code open-ended responses.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Standard UX Metrics">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use validated instruments verbatim — do not reword SUS, NPS, or UEQ items; any wording change invalidates benchmark comparability.</statement>
        <rationale>Benchmark databases (SUS mean=68, NPS range −100 to +100) are tied to exact wording; paraphrasing breaks the comparison.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>NPS: "How likely are you to recommend [X] to a friend or colleague?" (0-10). Score = % Promoters (9-10) minus % Detractors (0-6). Range: −100 to +100.</item>
        <item>SUS: 10 standardized alternating positive/negative items, 1-5 scale. Score = (pos_sum + neg_sum) × 2.5. Average = 68; above 80 = excellent; below 50 = poor.</item>
        <item>CSAT: "How satisfied are you with [X]?" (1-5 or 1-7). Score = (satisfied responses / total) × 100.</item>
        <item>SEQ: "Overall, how easy or difficult was this task?" (1-7, very difficult to very easy). Use after each task in usability testing. Benchmark = 5.5.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Question Quality Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Each question must address exactly one concept; split any question that could be answered differently if interpreted two ways.</statement>
        <rationale>Double-barreled questions ("speed and accuracy") produce uninterpretable data because the respondent cannot indicate which dimension drove their answer.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep total survey completion time under 5 minutes (median respondent); cut questions if the pilot exceeds this threshold.</statement>
        <rationale>Surveys over 5 minutes see sharply elevated dropout and straight-lining (respondents select the same answer for all items to finish faster).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Place demographic questions at the end of the survey, not the beginning.</statement>
        <rationale>Opening with demographics signals the survey is about the respondent rather than the product, reducing engagement with core questions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Randomize answer order on attitudinal items and Likert blocks to neutralize order and anchoring bias.</statement>
        <rationale>Fixed answer order produces systematic bias toward top or bottom options; randomization distributes this effect across respondents.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Response Rate Factors">
      <list>
        <item>Length — shorter surveys have higher completion rates; every additional question reduces response.</item>
        <item>Mobile-friendly format — many respondents complete on phone; fixed-width tables and non-tap-friendly controls cause abandonment.</item>
        <item>Clear stated purpose — respondents complete surveys that explain why their input matters.</item>
        <item>Mid-week, mid-day timing — Tuesday–Thursday, 10am–2pm local time consistently outperform other windows.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Good Question Examples">
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Question: "How often do you use the search feature?"
Options:
  - Never
  - Less than once a week
  - 1-3 times per week
  - Daily
  - Multiple times per day]]></code>
        <note>Single concept, unambiguous options with no gaps or overlaps, no assumed direction.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Question: "How satisfied are you with [product]?"
Options:
  - Very dissatisfied
  - Dissatisfied
  - Neutral
  - Satisfied
  - Very satisfied]]></code>
        <note>Standard CSAT wording; symmetric scale from negative to positive; all five points labelled.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Question Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Double-barreled: "How satisfied are you with the speed and accuracy of search results?"</description>
        <reason>Two dimensions in one question — a user who finds search fast but inaccurate cannot give a meaningful answer. Split into two separate questions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Leading: "How much do you love our new feature?"</description>
        <reason>Presupposes positive sentiment; drives respondents toward positive answers regardless of actual experience. Neutral wording: "How would you rate the new feature?"</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Vague: "How often do you use it?"</description>
        <reason>"It" is undefined; "often" is undefined. Every respondent interprets the question differently, producing incomparable data.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Double negative: "Is there anything you don't dislike about the onboarding?"</description>
        <reason>Double negatives require cognitive parsing effort that introduces noise and errors in responses. Rewrite as a direct positive or negative question.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Gotchas and Limitations">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Self-report bias: stated preferences differ from revealed behavior; survey results need triangulation.</description>
        <reason>Users often report different behaviors than they actually exhibit. Surveys must be paired with behavioral analytics for validation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Survey fatigue: long surveys collapse response rate and inflate straight-lining (same answer all the way down).</description>
        <reason>Fatigue introduces systematic error. Keep surveys under 5 minutes and pilot-test timing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sampling bias: who answers is rarely who you mean. Voluntary samples skew engaged + dissatisfied.</description>
        <reason>Survey respondents are self-selected. Compare respondent demographics to your user base to assess bias.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent invents a 7-point Likert scale when a 5-point was specified.</description>
        <reason>Scale changes invalidate benchmark comparability; constrain the agent to the exact scale defined in the research plan.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent codes open-ended responses and assigns confident themes to very short responses ("ok", emoji, single word).</description>
        <reason>LLMs hallucinate themes from sparse text; enforce a minimum word count before LLM coding and flag low-confidence items for human review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent computes NPS or SUS via LLM completion rather than deterministic code.</description>
        <reason>LLMs make arithmetic errors and confuse metric formulas; use the provided Python calculator for all metric computations.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent treats high survey NPS as a signal that users will pay for the product.</description>
        <reason>Stated preferences overestimate willingness-to-pay by 2-4x; willingness-to-pay research requires separate conjoint or pricing studies, not a satisfaction survey.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>Agents are most useful in three places: question drafting from research goals (with bias linting), pilot review, and open-ended response coding. Keep humans in the loop at instrument approval and at thematic-coding sign-off — LLM coding looks confident but invents themes when noise is high.</p>
      <p>Drive Claude to convert objectives into question candidates with type and bias notes. Use a dedicated bias-linter agent to flag double-barreled, leading, vague, and double-negative items. For open-ended responses, have an agent propose themes and code responses, but flag low-confidence items for human review.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: survey-question-drafter (converts objectives into question candidates with type and bias notes), survey-bias-linter (flags double-barreled, leading, vague, double-negative items), open-ended-coder (proposes themes, codes responses, flags low-confidence items for human review), nps-sus-calculator (computes standard metrics from raw CSV; deterministic, run as code not LLM).</p>
      <p>Prompt pattern: For each survey question, return JSON: {question, type, options?, bias_flags[]}. Bias flags: leading, double-barreled, double-negative, vague, jargon, loaded. If any flag fires, also return a rewritten neutral version. Do not invent options; respect the provided answer scale (Likert-5, NPS-0-10, binary).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Pilot with N=10 minimum and time the median respondent — kill any survey &gt;5 minutes.</item>
        <item>Randomize answer-order on attitudinal items and Likert blocks to neutralize order/anchoring bias.</item>
        <item>Always pair an attitudinal item ("how easy?") with a behavioral observation when possible — discrepancies are insight goldmines.</item>
        <item>Use validated instruments (SUS, UEQ, NPS, CSAT) verbatim; do not "improve" wording or you lose benchmark comparability.</item>
        <item>Track and report response and completion rates explicitly — silent dropoffs change interpretation.</item>
        <item>Instrument review by a researcher before launch — agent-drafted questions need bias check before fielding.</item>
        <item>Thematic-coding spot check: human reviews at least 10% of LLM-coded open-ended responses before finalizing themes.</item>
        <item>Non-English surveys: native-speaker review required, especially for SUS which is particularly sensitive to wording.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Survey Mistakes">
      <list>
        <item>Too long — target under 5 minutes; surveys over 10 minutes see 40%+ dropout.</item>
        <item>Too many open-ended questions — each open-ended adds analysis cost; limit to 1-2 per survey.</item>
        <item>No pilot test — unclear questions only become visible when real respondents encounter them.</item>
        <item>Wrong audience — sample that does not represent actual users produces misleading findings.</item>
        <item>No analysis plan — define how you will analyze results before fielding, not after; post-hoc fishing inflates false-positive rates.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/survey-plan.md" purpose="Survey plan: objective, audience, sample size, question list, success metrics"/>
      <template path="templates/survey_metrics.py" purpose="Deterministic NPS and SUS calculator from CSV; run as code, not LLM"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/qualitative-surveys/"/>
      <link href="https://measuringu.com/sus/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
